# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: bencie-woll
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:bencie-woll/2023-birthday-honours-p01] The **2023 King's Birthday Honours** are appointments by some of the 15 Commonwealth realms of King Charles III to various orders and honours to reward and highlight good works by citizens of those countries.
[src:bencie-woll/2023-birthday-honours-p01] The Birthday Honours are awarded as part of the King's Official Birthday celebrations during the month of June.
[src:bencie-woll/2023-birthday-honours-p01] The King appoints members to the orders upon the advice of his ministers.
[src:bencie-woll/2023-birthday-honours-p01] However, the Order of the Garter, the Order of the Thistle, the Order of Merit and the Royal Victorian Order are bestowed solely by the Sovereign.
[src:bencie-woll/2023-birthday-honours-p01] Below are the individuals appointed by Charles III in his right as King of the United Kingdom with honours within his own gift, and with the advice of the Government for other honours.
[src:bencie-woll/2023-birthday-honours-p03] The 2023 King's Birthday Honours for Australia was announced on 11 June 2023 by the Governor-General, David Hurley.
[src:bencie-woll/2023-birthday-honours-p03] The 2023 Birthday and Coronation Honours for New Zealand were announced on 5 June 2023 by the Governor-General, Dame Cindy Kiro.
[src:bencie-woll/2023-birthday-honours-p03] Below are the individuals appointed by Charles III in his right as King of the Realm of New Zealand, on the advice of His Majesty's Cook Islands Ministers.
[src:bencie-woll/2023-birthday-honours-p03] Below are the individuals appointed by Charles III in his right as King of the Bahamas, on the advice of His Majesty's Bahamas Ministers.
[src:bencie-woll/2023-birthday-honours-p03] Below are the individuals appointed by Charles III in his right as King of Grenada, on the advice of His Majesty's Grenada Ministers.
[src:bencie-woll/2023-birthday-honours-p03] Below are the individuals appointed by Charles III in his right as King of Papua New Guinea, on the advice of His Majesty's Papua New Guinea Ministers.
[src:bencie-woll/2023-birthday-honours-p04] Below are the individuals appointed by Charles III in his right as King of Solomon Islands, on the advice of His Majesty's Solomon Islands Ministers.
[src:bencie-woll/2023-birthday-honours-p04] Below are the individuals appointed by Charles III in his right as King of Saint Lucia, on the advice of His Majesty's Saint Lucia Ministers.
[src:bencie-woll/2023-birthday-honours-p04] Below are the individuals appointed by Charles III in his right as King of Belize, on the advice of His Majesty's Belize Ministers.
[src:bencie-woll/alma-mater] In its earliest usage, *alma mater* was an honorific title for various mother goddesses, especially Ceres or Cybele.
[src:bencie-woll/alma-mater] Later, in Catholicism, it became a title for Mary, mother of Jesus.
[src:bencie-woll/alma-mater] By the early 17th century, the nursing mother became an allegory for universities.
[src:bencie-woll/alma-mater] Used by many schools in Europe and North America, it has special association with the University of Bologna, whose motto *Alma Mater Studiorum* ("nurturing mother of studies") emphasizes its role in originating the modern university.
[src:bencie-woll/alma-mater] Several university campuses in North America display artistic representations of *Alma Mater*, depicted as a robed woman wearing a laurel wreath crown.
[src:bencie-woll/alma-mater] The earliest and of these is the bronze *Alma Mater* statue at Columbia University, designed in 1901 by Daniel Chester French.
[src:bencie-woll/alma-mater] In the US the term *alma mater* is often used to describe a school song.
[src:bencie-woll/alma-mater] Although *alma* (nourishing) was a common epithet for Ceres, Cybele, Venus, and other mother goddesses, it was not frequently used in conjunction with *mater* in classical Latin.
[src:bencie-woll/alma-mater] After the fall of Rome, the term was used in Christian liturgy to describe Jesus' mother, Mary.
[src:bencie-woll/alma-mater] "Alma Redemptoris Mater" is a well-known eleventh century antiphon devoted to Mary.
[src:bencie-woll/alma-mater] The earliest documented use of the term to refer to a university is in 1600, when the University of Cambridge printer, John Legate, began using an emblem for the university press.
[src:bencie-woll/alma-mater] The first-known appearance of the device is in William Perkins', *A Golden Chain*, a book first printed by Legate in 1600.
[src:bencie-woll/alma-mater] On the title-page, the Latin phrase *Alma Mater Cantabrigia* ("nourishing mother Cambridge") is inscribed on a pedestal bearing a lactating woman wearing a mural crown.
[src:bencie-woll/alma-mater] In reference works of English etymology, often the first university-related usage is cited as 1710, when an academic mother figure is mentioned in a remembrance of Henry More by Richard Ward.
[src:bencie-woll/alma-mater] Many historic European universities have adopted *Alma Mater* as part of the Latin translation of their official name.
[src:bencie-woll/alma-mater] The Latin name of the University of Bologna, *Alma Mater Studiorum* (nourishing mother of studies), refers to its status as the oldest continuously operating university in the world.
[src:bencie-woll/alma-mater] At other European universities, such as the Alma Mater Lipsiensis in Leipzig, Germany, or Alma Mater Jagiellonica, Poland, the title emphasizes historic ties to a founding city or dynasty.
[src:bencie-woll/alma-mater] The Alma Mater Europaea in Salzburg, Austria, an international university founded by the European Academy of Sciences and Arts in 2010, uses the term as its official name.
[src:bencie-woll/alma-mater] In the United States, the College of William & Mary in Williamsburg, Virginia, has been called the "Alma Mater of the Nation" because of its ties to the founding of the country.
[src:bencie-woll/alma-mater] At Queen's University in Kingston, Ontario, and the University of British Columbia in Vancouver, British Columbia, the main student government is known as the Alma Mater Society.
[src:bencie-woll/alma-mater] Sculptures of *Alma Mater* are found on several North American university campuses.
[src:bencie-woll/alma-mater] In 1901, to commemorate the opening of the Low Library, Columbia University commissioned Daniel Chester French to design a bronze statue for the library's steps.
[src:bencie-woll/alma-mater] French chose the *Alma Mater* to allegorically embody the university without depicting its founder, King George II.
[src:bencie-woll/alma-mater] A similar sculpture, cast in 1919 by Mario Korbel, sits on the main entrance steps at the University of Havana.
[src:bencie-woll/alma-mater] Other tributes to *Alma Mater* include Lorado Taft's *1929 sculpture* at the University of Illinois Urbana-Champaign and Cyrus Dallin's 1925 sculpture at the Mary Institute in 1925, commissioned by Washington University supporters.
[src:bencie-woll/alma-mater] An altarpiece mural in Yale University's Sterling Memorial Library, painted in 1932 by Eugene Savage, depicts the *Alma Mater* as a bearer of light and truth, standing in the midst of figures representing the arts and sciences.
[src:bencie-woll/bachelor-of-arts] A **Bachelor of Arts** (abbreviated **BA** or **AB**; from the Latin **baccalaureus artium**, **baccalaureus in artibus**, or **artium baccalaureus**) is the holder of a bachelor's degree awarded for an undergraduate program in the liberal arts, or, in some cases, other disciplines.
[src:bencie-woll/bachelor-of-arts] A Bachelor of Arts degree course is generally completed in three or four years, depending on the country and institution.
[src:bencie-woll/bachelor-of-arts] The Bachelor of Arts (BA) degree is an undergraduate postsecondary degree that puts a focus on liberal arts and studies.
[src:bencie-woll/bachelor-of-arts] In comparison, a Bachelor of Science (BS or BSc) has a greater focus on science, math, and engineering.
[src:bencie-woll/bachelor-of-arts] The Bachelor of Arts degree is a type of baccalaureate degree.
[src:bencie-woll/bachelor-of-arts] A Bachelor of Arts degree is usually completed in four years: that is, it requires four years of full-time coursework during term time.
[src:bencie-woll/bachelor-of-arts] However, just as with other degrees, some may require a longer time period.
[src:bencie-woll/bachelor-of-arts] This is due to factors such as the student's ability, motivation, and access to financial assistance to earn the degree.
[src:bencie-woll/bachelor-of-arts] Just like other baccalaureate degrees, a Bachelor of Arts is historically offered only at public and private universities and colleges.
[src:bencie-woll/bachelor-of-arts] A Bachelor of Arts, just like other bachelor's degrees, is an admission requirement for graduate and professional school.
[src:bencie-woll/bachelor-of-arts] Beginning in the 1990s, junior colleges started to confer their own baccalaureate degrees.
[src:bencie-woll/bachelor-of-arts] In addition to the standard BA degrees, there are career-specific Bachelors of Arts degree, including Bachelor of Arts in Functional English, Bachelor of Arts in Administration, Bachelor of Arts in Interdisciplinary Studies, and Regents Bachelor of Arts.
[src:bencie-woll/bachelor-of-arts] The Bachelor of Arts degree has been prominent in academics for centuries.
[src:bencie-woll/bachelor-of-arts] It influenced universities to begin focusing on broad topics such as algebra, psychology, biology, art, history, and philosophy.
[src:bencie-woll/bachelor-of-arts] This aspect of the BA degree has been consistent in its history.
[src:bencie-woll/bachelor-of-arts] The Bachelor of Arts degree was formed out of the study of liberal arts.
[src:bencie-woll/bachelor-of-arts] *Liberal art* is a term that was applied to the study of many branches of learning such as grammar, logic, rhetoric, arithmetic, geometry, astronomy, and music.
[src:bencie-woll/bachelor-of-arts] The study of liberal arts started during the Middle Ages.
[src:bencie-woll/bachelor-of-arts] During the Renaissance, the term *liberal* *art* was meant to describe general studies more broadly.
[src:bencie-woll/bachelor-of-arts] This definition of liberal studies remains to this day.
[src:bencie-woll/bachelor-of-arts] In Japan and the United States, Bachelor of Arts degrees were historically given only by public or private institutions and colleges.
[src:bencie-woll/bachelor-of-arts] In Germany, university-level education usually happens in either a *Universität* (plural: *Universitäten*) or a *Fachhochschule* (plural: *Fachhochschulen*); both can be referred to as a *Hochschule*, which is the generic term in Germany for all institutions awarding academic degrees.
[src:bencie-woll/bachelor-of-arts] *Fachhochschule* is often translated as "University of Applied Sciences".
[src:bencie-woll/bachelor-of-arts] *Universitäten* place greater emphasis on fundamental science and background in theory, while *Fachhochschulen* are generally designed with a focus on teaching professional skills.
[src:bencie-woll/bachelor-of-arts] Degrees earned at *Universitäten* and *Fachhochschulen* are legally equivalent.
[src:bencie-woll/bachelor-of-arts] In Germany, the BA course normally lasts between three and three and a half years—six or seven semesters—and the degree is awarded after the student earns between 180 and 210 ECTS.
[src:bencie-woll/bachelor-of-arts] In the Netherlands, the BA and Master of Arts (MA) degrees were introduced in 2002.
[src:bencie-woll/bachelor-of-arts] Until then, a single program led to the *doctorandus* degree (abbreviated drs.), which comprised the same course load as the bachelor's and master's programs combined.
[src:bencie-woll/bachelor-of-arts] The title *doctorandus* was used in almost all fields of study; other titles were used for legal studies (*meester*, Dutch for master, abbreviated *Mr.*) and engineering (*ingenieur*, abbreviated Ir. for academic masters level or ING. for higher vocational bachelor's level).
[src:bencie-woll/bachelor-of-arts] Those who had already started the *doctorandus* program could, on completing it, opt for the *doctorandus* degree (entitling them to use "drs." in front of their name) or could use the master's degree (post-nominal letters) in accordance with the new standard.
[src:bencie-woll/bachelor-of-arts] When attaining a master level/graduate degree, it is still customary to use either drs. pre-nominally or MA/MSc post-nominally at the discretion of the holder.
[src:bencie-woll/bachelor-of-arts] In the United Kingdom (excluding Scotland) and Ireland, the first degree course normally lasts three years, but nomenclature varies: 19th-century and later universities usually distinguish between arts and sciences subjects by awarding either a BA or BSc degree.
[src:bencie-woll/bachelor-of-arts] Some new plate glass universities established in the 1960s, such as York and Lancaster, originally followed the practice of Oxford and Cambridge by awarding BAs in all subjects, but have since changed to awarding BSc degrees in science subjects.
[src:bencie-woll/bachelor-of-arts] At Oxford, Cambridge, and Dublin the degree of MA can be claimed, usually twenty-one terms after matriculation, without any further study.
[src:bencie-woll/bachelor-of-arts] For many centuries, the bachelor's degree was an intermediate step and was awarded for much of the work carried out in later times at secondary schools.
[src:bencie-woll/bachelor-of-arts] The names of the final secondary school exams in France and Spain (and of the International Baccalaureate) come from this: *le Baccalauréat* and *el Bachillerato*, respectively.
[src:bencie-woll/bachelor-of-arts] The ancient universities of Scotland award a Master of Arts degree to humanities or arts graduates, but a BSc to science graduates.
[src:bencie-woll/bachelor-of-arts] This course takes four years for an honours degree and three for an ordinary.
[src:bencie-woll/bachelor-of-arts] In Scotland, one can opt to take an ordinary degree, which ranks below a third class honours degree (for example, BA with distinction, merit or pass).
[src:bencie-woll/bachelor-of-arts] A Bachelor of Arts is entitled to the post-nominal letters BA for an ordinary or pass degree and BA (Hons) for an honours degree.
[src:bencie-woll/bachelor-of-arts] The academic dress worn by honours and non-honours graduates is identical.
[src:bencie-woll/bachelor-of-arts] An honours degree is always awarded in one of four classes, depending upon the marks gained in the final assessments and examinations.
[src:bencie-woll/bachelor-of-arts] The top students are awarded a first-class degree, followed by an upper second-class degree (usually referred to as a 2:1), a lower second-class degree (usually referred to as a 2:2), and those who pass with the lowest marks gain a third-class degree.
[src:bencie-woll/bachelor-of-arts] An ordinary, pass or unclassified degree (which does not give the graduate the right to add "Hons") may be awarded if a student has completed (i) followed a non-honours program, or (b) attempted an honours course but marginally failed to achieve third-class standard.
[src:bencie-woll/bachelor-of-arts] Education in Canada is controlled by the provinces and can be very different depending on the province.
[src:bencie-woll/bachelor-of-arts] While all Canadian universities offer four-year degrees, it is not uncommon, depending on the province and the university for a three-year general degree to also be offered as an option.
[src:bencie-woll/bachelor-of-arts] In many universities and colleges, Bachelor of Arts degrees are differentiated either as BA or as honours BA degrees.
[src:bencie-woll/bachelor-of-arts] Honours programs require more education than non-honours programs, typically a specialization beyond the requirements of a BA, and can sometimes be used as a gateway to a PhD program, bypassing a master's degree.
[src:bencie-woll/bachelor-of-arts] In Québec, BA degrees generally last three years, because the fourth year is replaced by CEGEP education (which fills the gap between Secondary V, the last year of high school, and the first year of university).
[src:bencie-woll/bachelor-of-arts] However, four-year programs exist for students having completed 12 (instead of 13) years of education prior to being admitted to university.
[src:bencie-woll/bachelor-of-arts] Along with the Bachelor of Science (BS), the Bachelor of Arts (BA) is the most commonly granted degree in the United States.
[src:bencie-woll/bachelor-of-arts] A BA degree is usually earned after the completion of four years of undergraduate college level study.
[src:bencie-woll/bachelor-of-arts] Some universities in the United States abbreviate the degree as "AB" or "A.B.", derived from the Latin title *Artium Baccalaureatus*.
[src:bencie-woll/bachelor-of-arts] AB degrees are particularly associated with Ivy League institutions and other universities with historical ties to Latin academic traditions—such as Harvard, Princeton, Brown, the University of Chicago, WashU, and Bryn Mawr College.
[src:bencie-woll/bachelor-of-arts] These schools use the AB (or A.B.) designation to distinguish their degree from the more common Bachelor of Arts (BA).
[src:bencie-woll/bachelor-of-arts] The use of Latin terminology underscores their heritage and the prestige of their academic programs, where the study of Greek and Latin had traditionally been a fundamental component of the undergraduate curriculum at these institutions.
[src:bencie-woll/bachelor-of-arts] The College of Charleston also offers the A.B. degree as an option with the requirement that students demonstrate proficiency in either Latin or Greek.
[src:bencie-woll/bachelor-of-arts] In colleges and universities in Australia, Nepal, New Zealand, India and South Africa, the BA degree can be taken over three years of full-time study.
[src:bencie-woll/bachelor-of-arts] Students must pursue at least one major area of study and units from that subject are usually studied in each year, though sometimes students may choose to complete upper-level classes in the same year and as a result, can leave space for elective subjects from a different field.
[src:bencie-woll/bachelor-of-arts] At some universities, students may choose to pursue a second major; alternatively, the remainder of the degree is taken up with a minor area of study (in the first two years) and other individual or stream-based subjects.
[src:bencie-woll/bachelor-of-arts] In Pakistan the Bachelor of Arts (BA) program used to be regular 2-year degree program in which students were offered with a combination of any two of areas from the available electives: Business, Journalism, Psychology, Computer Science and Education.
[src:bencie-woll/bachelor-of-arts] However, now all bachelor's degree courses are 4-year program.
[src:bencie-woll/bachelor-of-arts] 2 years degree is now called associate degree.
[src:bencie-woll/bencie-woll] Woll was born in 1950 in New York City, United States.
[src:bencie-woll/bencie-woll] She studied at the University of Pennsylvania, where she majored in linguistics and graduated with a Bachelor of Arts (BA) degree in 1970.
[src:bencie-woll/bencie-woll] She then moved to the United Kingdom where she studied theoretical linguistics at the University of Essex, graduating with a Master of Arts (MA) degree in 1971.
[src:bencie-woll/bencie-woll] During her time teaching at the University of Bristol, she studied for a Doctor of Philosophy (PhD) degree in sign language linguistics.
[src:bencie-woll/bencie-woll] Woll's academic research is focused on the linguistics of sign language.
[src:bencie-woll/bencie-woll] She has researched the history and sociolinguistics of British Sign Language (BSL), sociolinguistics of Deaf communities, language development in deaf children, the neuroscience of sign language and developmental and acquired sign language impairments.
[src:bencie-woll/bencie-woll] From 1973 to 1995, Woll worked at the University of Bristol as a research associate, research fellow, lecturer, and then senior lecturer.
[src:bencie-woll/bencie-woll] In 1995, she was appointed to City University, London, as Professor of Sign Language and Deaf Studies.
[src:bencie-woll/bencie-woll] She thereby became the first person in the United Kingdom to hold a chair in sign language.
[src:bencie-woll/bencie-woll] In August 2005, she moved to University College London (UCL) where she was appointed Professor of Sign Language and Deaf Studies.
[src:bencie-woll/bencie-woll] In 2006, she founded the Deafness Cognition and Language Research Centre at UCL: she served as its director from 2006 to 2016.
[src:bencie-woll/bencie-woll] Woll offers her services as an expert witness in court cases involving deaf people and British Sign Language.
[src:bencie-woll/bencie-woll] She served as Vice Chair of the Royal Association for Deaf People between 2002 and 2008.
[src:bencie-woll/bencie-woll] Since 2011, she has been a trustee of the UK Council on Deafness.
[src:bencie-woll/bencie-woll] Woll was awarded the 2000 BAAL Book Prize for *The Linguistics of British Sign Language: An Introduction*.
[src:bencie-woll/bencie-woll] In 2012, she was elected a Fellow of the British Academy (FBA), the United Kingdom's national academy for the humanities and social sciences.
[src:bencie-woll/bencie-woll] In 2016, she was elected a Fellow of the American Association for the Advancement of Science.
[src:bencie-woll/bencie-woll] She was appointed Member of the Order of the British Empire (MBE) in the 2023 Birthday Honours for services to higher education and deaf people.
[src:bencie-woll/british-association-for-applied-linguistics] The **British Association for Applied Linguistics** (**BAAL**) is a learned society, based in the UK, which provides a forum for people interested in language and applied linguistics.
[src:bencie-woll/british-association-for-applied-linguistics] BAAL organises regular meetings of its members at various venues in the UK, publishes conference proceedings, issues a regular newsletter and awards student scholarships.
[src:bencie-woll/british-association-for-applied-linguistics] There is an elected Executive Committee (EC) that represents the interests of members.
[src:bencie-woll/british-association-for-applied-linguistics] The current chair is Professor Zhu Hua of UCL Institute of Education.
[src:bencie-woll/british-association-for-applied-linguistics] BAAL has an international membership of over 1200 members and is a registered charity in the UK (Charity number 246800).
[src:bencie-woll/british-association-for-applied-linguistics] It supports applied linguistics activity.
[src:bencie-woll/british-association-for-applied-linguistics] It brings together the applied linguistics community viaBAALmail, its dedicated webmail list, through which members share and discuss applied linguistics-related news, achievements and opportunities.
[src:bencie-woll/british-association-for-applied-linguistics] BAAL is also officially represented on the advisory board of the journal Applied Linguistics (Oxford University Press).
[src:bencie-woll/british-association-for-applied-linguistics] Since 1967 BAAL has held an annual conference.
[src:bencie-woll/british-association-for-applied-linguistics] At the conference three prizes are awarded: the annual Book Prize, the Richard Pemberton prize for the best postgraduate student paper and a prize for the best poster presentation.
[src:bencie-woll/british-association-for-applied-linguistics] BAAL has a number of Special Interest Groups (SIGs), which meet regularly and provide opportunities for researchers to share, promote and develop work within specific areas of applied linguistics.
[src:bencie-woll/british-association-for-applied-linguistics] BAAL was founded in the 1960s, as interest increased in the science of linguistics and its practical applications - for example, in language teaching and learning.
[src:bencie-woll/british-association-for-applied-linguistics] BAAL's creation was the result of a proposal by Peter Strevens, recently appointed to a new chair in Applied Linguistics at the University of Essex.
[src:bencie-woll/british-association-for-applied-linguistics] At a preliminary meeting of interested parties at Birkbeck College in July 1965, a narrower remit was discussed than the wider set of issues that the Association would ultimately concern itself with.
[src:bencie-woll/british-association-for-applied-linguistics] Initially, it was suggested that it might focus on language teaching and machine translation, but the first full meeting in 1967 at the University of Reading agreed to broaden the scope.
[src:bencie-woll/british-association-for-applied-linguistics] BAAL emerged as the UK affiliate of AILA, with Pit Corder its first chair.
[src:bencie-woll/british-association-for-applied-linguistics] Membership was narrowly defined in the early years, but a feeling that the Association could afford to widen recruitment was apparent by the early 1970s.
[src:bencie-woll/british-association-for-applied-linguistics] In 1985, a requirement for formal qualifications, already flexible, was dropped; and today anyone can join.
[src:bencie-woll/british-association-for-applied-linguistics] The BAAL Archive is housed in the Centre for Applied Linguistics, University of Warwick.
[src:bencie-woll/british-sign-language] In 2016 the British Deaf Association (BDA) said that, based on official statistics, it believes there are 151,000 people who use BSL in the UK, and 87,000 of these are deaf.
[src:bencie-woll/british-sign-language] This figure does not include professional BSL users, interpreters, translators, etc. unless they use BSL at home.
[src:bencie-woll/british-sign-language] By contrast, in the 2011 England and Wales Census 15,000 people living in England and Wales reported themselves using BSL as their main language.
[src:bencie-woll/british-sign-language] In Northern Ireland, there are about 4,500 users of BSL and 1,500 users of Irish Sign Language, an unrelated sign language.
[src:bencie-woll/british-sign-language] A hybrid version, dubbed "Northern Ireland Sign Language", is also used.
[src:bencie-woll/british-sign-language] On 18 March 2003 the UK government formally recognised BSL as a language in its own right.
[src:bencie-woll/british-sign-language] In 2022, the British Sign Language Act was passed, which legally recognised BSL as a language of England, Wales and Scotland.
[src:bencie-woll/british-sign-language] BSL is used in some educational establishments, but is not always the policy for deaf children in some local authority areas.
[src:bencie-woll/british-sign-language] As of January 2026, there is no GCSE qualification in British Sign Language available to students, but one is under development in England and planned for Wales.
[src:bencie-woll/british-sign-language] The Department for Education began to develop the GCSE in 2019, but the process was delayed due to the Covid-19 pandemic.
[src:bencie-woll/british-sign-language] In June 2023, the UK Government launched a consultation for the GCSE, with teaching initially planned to begin in schools from September 2025.
[src:bencie-woll/british-sign-language] In 2024, Qualifications Wales suspended development of its GCSE in BSL, setting a new goal to introduce it to schools in Wales in 2027.
[src:bencie-woll/british-sign-language] In 2025, Ofqual ran a second consultation to gather feedback on its proposed rules for the qualification in England, releasing the results and its final decisions on the rules in November.
[src:bencie-woll/british-sign-language] GCSE exam boards who want to run the qualification in England must next make detailed offers to Ofqual for accreditation based on these regulations.
[src:bencie-woll/british-sign-language] Many British television channels broadcast programmes with in-vision signing, using BSL, as well as specially made programmes aimed mainly at deaf people such as the BBC's *See Hear* and Channel 4's *VEE-TV*.
[src:bencie-woll/british-sign-language] There is also a specially dedicated British Sign Language channel, LumoTV (previously BSL Zone), established in 2008.
[src:bencie-woll/british-sign-language] All BBC channels (excluding BBC One and BBC Alba) provide in-vision signing for some of their programmes.
[src:bencie-woll/british-sign-language] BBC Two also broadcasts in-vision signed repeats of the main channel's primetime programmes between 00:00 and 05:00 each weekday and early Saturday mornings.
[src:bencie-woll/british-sign-language] It also provides signing on weekday mornings between 08:00 and 09:00.
[src:bencie-woll/british-sign-language] In 2024, over 10% of Channel 4's programming was signed, including popular shows such as Hollyoaks and Gogglebox.
[src:bencie-woll/british-sign-language] Published in 1992, the British Sign Language Dictionary was compiled for the British Deaf Association by the Deaf Studies Research Unit at the University of Durham.
[src:bencie-woll/british-sign-language] The dictionary was edited by David Brien, assisted by a team composed by Mary Brennan, Clark Denmark, Frances Elton, Liz Scott Gibson, Graham Turner and Dorothy Miles, among others.
[src:bencie-woll/british-sign-language] It depicts over 1,800 signs through pictures and diagrams, each sign accompanied by definitions, explanations and usage.
[src:bencie-woll/british-sign-language] The signs are ordered not alphabetically, as a dictionary of the English language, but rather according to the phonological characteristics of the language.
[src:bencie-woll/british-sign-language] For example, signs that are based on the "fist" handshape come before signs based on the "open hand" handshape.
[src:bencie-woll/british-sign-language] The foreword was written by Diana, Princess of Wales, who was the patron of the BDA.
[src:bencie-woll/british-sign-language] The British Sign Language Corpus Project, based at the Deafness Cognition and Language Research Centre (University College London), was funded between 2008 and 2011 to provide a video corpus of BSL in four regions (Bristol, Birmingham, London and Manchester).
[src:bencie-woll/british-sign-language] It was succeeded by the BSL SignBank, which moved the BSL Corpus online between 2011 and 2015.
[src:bencie-woll/british-sign-language] It also draws on the 1992 BSL Dictionary for its vocabulary.
[src:bencie-woll/british-sign-language] Certain signs used in Scotland, for example, may not be understood immediately, or not understood at all, by those in Southern England, or vice versa.
[src:bencie-woll/british-sign-language] Some signs are even more local, occurring only in certain towns or cities (such as the Manchester system of number signs).
[src:bencie-woll/british-sign-language] Likewise, some may go in or out of fashion, or evolve over time, just as terms in oral languages do.
[src:bencie-woll/british-sign-language] Families may have signs unique to them to accommodate for certain situations or to describe an object that may otherwise require fingerspelling.
[src:bencie-woll/british-sign-language] Although the United Kingdom and the United States share English as the predominant spoken language, British Sign Language is quite distinct from American Sign Language (ASL), having only 31% signs identical, or 44% cognate.
[src:bencie-woll/british-sign-language] BSL is also distinct from Irish Sign Language (ISL), which is more closely related to French Sign Language (LSF) and ASL.
[src:bencie-woll/british-sign-language] BSL is also distinct from Signed English, a manually coded method expressed to represent the English language.
[src:bencie-woll/british-sign-language] The sign languages used in Australia and New Zealand, Auslan and New Zealand Sign Language respectively, evolved largely from 19th century BSL, and all retain the same manual alphabet and grammar and possess similar lexicons.
[src:bencie-woll/british-sign-language] The sign language used in Sri Lanka is also closely related to BSL despite the oral language not being English, demonstrating variation in distance between sign languages and spoken ones.
[src:bencie-woll/british-sign-language] While private correspondence from William Stokoe hinted at a formal name for the language in 1960, the first usage of the term "British Sign Language" in an academic publication was likely by Aaron Cicourel.
[src:bencie-woll/british-sign-language] The earliest known document describing the use of signing in a legal context is dated to c.
[src:bencie-woll/british-sign-language] 1324 and mentions John de Orleton, a deaf man assigning his property to a family member.
[src:bencie-woll/british-sign-language] Published in 1450, the *History of the Syon Monastery at Lisbon and Brentford*, contains descriptions of signs—some of which are still in use.
[src:bencie-woll/british-sign-language] The earliest evidence of signing in registry records is from a marriage ceremony between a deaf man, Thomas Tilsye and Ursula Russel on 6 February 1576 at St Martin's Church, now Leicester Cathedral.
[src:bencie-woll/british-sign-language] Richard Carew's *Survey of Cornwall* (1602) includes a description of Edward Bone, a deaf servant, meeting his deaf friend John Kempe.
[src:bencie-woll/british-sign-language] Bone had some knowledge of Cornish and was able to lipread, but appeared to prefer signing.
[src:bencie-woll/british-sign-language] In particular, *Chirologia* focuses on the meanings of gestures, expressions and body language, and describes signs and gestures in use at the time, some of which resemble signs still in use, while *Philocopus* explores the use of lipreading by deaf people and the possibility of deaf education.
[src:bencie-woll/british-sign-language] Another writer of the same time, George Dalgarno, recognised that sign language was unrelated to English.
[src:bencie-woll/british-sign-language] British Sign Language has evolved, as all languages do, from these origins by modification, invention and importation.
[src:bencie-woll/british-sign-language] Thomas Braidwood, a teacher from Edinburgh, founded 'Braidwood's Academy for the Deaf and Dumb' in 1760, which is believed to be the first school for deaf children in Britain.
[src:bencie-woll/british-sign-language] The school primarily taught oral communication, however there is evidence of 'deaf signing' being used as a teaching method (albeit probably following the structure of English).
[src:bencie-woll/british-sign-language] This *combined system* came to be known as the English method—a sort of midway point between French manualist and German oralist systems, and was the first codification of what would later develop into British Sign Language.
[src:bencie-woll/british-sign-language] Joseph Watson was trained as a teacher of the deaf under Thomas Braidwood.
[src:bencie-woll/british-sign-language] He eventually left in 1792 to become the headmaster of the Asylum for the Deaf and Dumb in Bermondsey where he advocated for 'natural signing'—likely referring to the way deaf children naturally sign, as opposed to following English structure.
[src:bencie-woll/british-sign-language] This 'natural signing' is thought to be the precursor to modern BSL.
[src:bencie-woll/british-sign-language] In 1815 when Thomas Gallaudet visited England, the Braidwood school refused to teach him their methods unless he paid them.
[src:bencie-woll/british-sign-language] So instead, Gallaudet found himself in Paris, having been invited there by the much more accommodating Abbé Sicard.
[src:bencie-woll/british-sign-language] Gallaudet would eventually take much of the what had learnt in France, back to the United States.
[src:bencie-woll/british-sign-language] As a consequence American Sign Language (ASL) today has a 60% similarity to modern French Sign Language and is almost unintelligible to users of British Sign Language.
[src:bencie-woll/british-sign-language] By the mid 1800s, sign was the most prominent mode of communication within deaf schools in Britain, and by 1870, there were 22 (often residential) schools found in most major cities around the country.
[src:bencie-woll/british-sign-language] The Second International Congress on Education of the Deaf, also known as the Milan Conference, was held in 1880, and proscribed the use of sign language in education; for the best part of a century, sign language was no longer used in the education of deaf children.
[src:bencie-woll/british-sign-language] Signing was actively discouraged in schools by punishment, and deaf education emphasised teaching deaf children to learn to lip read and finger spell, due to the prevailing belief across Europe established that signing was bad.
[src:bencie-woll/british-sign-language] Since there was no (or very little) exchange of sign language within educational establishments, signing was preserved through deaf clubs or within families.
[src:bencie-woll/british-sign-language] Until the 1940s, sign language skills were passed between deaf people without a unified sign language system and many deaf people lived in residential institutions.
[src:bencie-woll/british-sign-language] In 1978, the government-issued Warnock Report advocated for the mainstreaming of deaf children which led to the closure of many deaf schools.
[src:bencie-woll/british-sign-language] During this time, the Total Communication method was popularised.
[src:bencie-woll/british-sign-language] From the 1970s there has been an increasing tolerance for the language, in part due to its recognition as a natural language by linguists.
[src:bencie-woll/british-sign-language] In the 1980s, BSL started to be used as language of instruction in schools again, alongside English.
[src:bencie-woll/british-sign-language] This decade saw the start of deaf programming on British television.
[src:bencie-woll/british-sign-language] Deaf scholar and activist Paddy Ladd is credited with getting sign language on television and enabling deaf children to be educated in sign.
[src:bencie-woll/british-sign-language] BSL users campaigned to have BSL recognised on an official level.
[src:bencie-woll/british-sign-language] Police and Criminal Evidence Act 1984 mandates the provision of interpreters.
[src:bencie-woll/british-sign-language] In 1999, the Federation of Deaf People (FDP) led a 4000-strong march in London to demand the recognition of BSL as a language.
[src:bencie-woll/british-sign-language] This can be considered to mark the first political march by the modern 'British Deaf Community', as an established community.
[src:bencie-woll/british-sign-language] Let Sign Shine is a campaign started by Norfolk teenager Jade Chapman, whose sister is deaf, to raise awareness of BSL and to petition for BSL to be taught in schools.
[src:bencie-woll/british-sign-language] The campaign's petition to Parliament attracted support from over four thousand people.
[src:bencie-woll/british-sign-language] Chapman won awards for her work including the education award category at the Bernard Matthews Youth Award 2014 for her work in raising awareness of the importance of sign language.
[src:bencie-woll/british-sign-language] Having been donated £1,000 from the Bernard Matthews Youth Award, Let Sign Shine used this to start a British Sign Language course at Dereham Neatherd High School.
[src:bencie-woll/british-sign-language] In 2021, MP Rosie Cooper (a CODA) introduced the British Sign Language Bill to recognise BSL, this time as an official language (not merely its existence as had been done in 2003), which was backed by the government.
[src:bencie-woll/british-sign-language] After being dormant from June 2021, the bill began moving through Parliament on 28 January 2022, but during a meeting with stakeholders on 7 February, the language of the bill was revealed to have been pared down substantially, disappointing said stakeholders.
[src:bencie-woll/british-sign-language] The British Deaf Association stated that it was 'unhappy' with this removal of language from the bill.
[src:bencie-woll/british-sign-language] The British Sign Language Act received royal assent on 28th April 2022.
[src:bencie-woll/british-sign-language] Linguistics is the study of language, including those like BSL that are not carried by sound.
[src:bencie-woll/british-sign-language] In all sign languages the great majority of 'words' (hand gestures) cannot be understood in other sign languages.
[src:bencie-woll/british-sign-language] How one language signs a certain number would be different from how another language signs it.
[src:bencie-woll/british-sign-language] The way sentences are constructed (syntax) differs from sign language to sign language, just as with different spoken languages.
[src:bencie-woll/british-sign-language] British Sign Language is described as a 'spatial language' as it "moves signs in space".
[src:bencie-woll/british-sign-language] Like many other sign languages, BSL phonology is defined by elements such as handshape, orientation, location, movement, and non-manual features.
[src:bencie-woll/british-sign-language] There are phonological components to sign language that have no meaning alone but work together to create a meaning of a signed word: hand shape, movement, location, orientation and facial expression.
[src:bencie-woll/british-sign-language] The meanings of words differ if one of these components is changed.
[src:bencie-woll/british-sign-language] Signs can be identical in certain components but different in others, giving each a different meaning.
[src:bencie-woll/british-sign-language] Facial expression falls under the nonmanual feature component of phonology.
[src:bencie-woll/british-sign-language] In common with other languages, whether spoken or signed, BSL has its own grammar which govern how phrases are signed.
[src:bencie-woll/british-sign-language] One important component of BSL is its use of proforms.
[src:bencie-woll/british-sign-language] A proform is "...any form that stands in the place of, or does the job of, some other form." Sentences are composed of two parts, in order: the subject and the predicate.
[src:bencie-woll/british-sign-language] The subject is the topic of the sentence, while the predicate is the commentary about the subject.
[src:bencie-woll/british-sign-language] Question words are generally at the end of a sentence.
[src:bencie-woll/british-sign-language] Topic-comment means that the topic of the signed conversation is first established, followed by an elaboration of the topic, being the 'comment' component.
[src:bencie-woll/british-sign-language] The canonical word order outside of the topic–comment structure is object–subject–verb (OSV), and noun phrases are head-initial.
[src:bencie-woll/british-sign-language] The language continues to evolve as older signs such as *alms* and *pawnbroker* have fallen out of use and new signs such as *internet* and *laser* have been coined.
[src:bencie-woll/british-sign-language] The evolution of the language and its changing level of acceptance meant that older users tend to use more finger spelling while younger ones make use of a wider range of signs.
[src:bencie-woll/british-sign-language] In 2019, over 100 signs for scientific terms, including 'deoxyribonucleotide' and 'deoxyribonucleoside', were added to BSL, after being conceived by Liam Mcmulkin, a deaf graduate of the University of Dundee, who had found finger-spelling such words tiresome, during his degree course.
[src:bencie-woll/british-sign-language] Similarly, architects Chris Laing and Adolfs Kristapsons developed a project called SignStrokes which developed new signs for the built environment, having not wanted to continuously make new signs for different architectural concepts.
[src:bencie-woll/british-sign-language] British Sign Language can be learnt from formal institutions throughout the UK and three examination systems exist.
[src:bencie-woll/british-sign-language] Courses are provided by community colleges, local centres for deaf people and private organisations.
[src:bencie-woll/british-sign-language] A teaching qualification programme was started by the British Deaf Association in 1984 at the University of Durham, called BSL Tutor Training Course, which closed in 1999.
[src:bencie-woll/british-sign-language] National awarding organisations run training for BSL teachers.
[src:bencie-woll/british-sign-language] Each of these organisations has its own curriculum, teaching materials and resources.
[src:bencie-woll/british-sign-language] There are two qualification routes: via post-graduate studies, or via National Vocational Qualifications.
[src:bencie-woll/british-sign-language] Deaf studies undergraduate courses with specific streams for sign language interpreting exist at several British universities; post-graduate level interpreting diplomas are also on offer from universities and one private company.
[src:bencie-woll/british-sign-language] Course entry requirements vary from no previous knowledge of BSL to NVQ level 6 BSL (or equivalent).
[src:bencie-woll/british-sign-language] The qualification process allows interpreters to register with the National Registers of Communication Professionals with Deaf and Deafblind People (NRCPD), a voluntary regulator.
[src:bencie-woll/british-sign-language] Registrants are asked to self-certify that they have both cleared a DBS (Disclosure and Barring Service) check and are covered by professional indemnity insurance.
[src:bencie-woll/british-sign-language] Completing a level 3 BSL language assessment and enrolling on an approved interpreting course allows applications to register as a TSLI (Trainee Sign Language Interpreter).
[src:bencie-woll/british-sign-language] After completing an approved interpreting course, trainees can then apply to achieve RSLI (Registered Sign Language Interpreter) status.
[src:bencie-woll/british-sign-language] RSLIs are currently required by NRCPD to log Continuous Professional Development activities.
[src:bencie-woll/british-sign-language] Post-qualification, specialist training is still considered necessary to work in specific critical domains.
[src:bencie-woll/british-sign-language] Communication support workers (CSWs) are professionals who support the communication of deaf students in education at all ages, and deaf people in many areas of work, using British Sign Language and other communication methods such as Sign Supported English.
[src:bencie-woll/british-sign-language] The qualifications and experience of CSWs vary: some are fully qualified interpreters, others are not.
[src:bencie-woll/british-sign-language] There are currently two well-established BSL language learning apps and web platforms: Bright BSL and Lingvano.
[src:bencie-woll/city-university-london] City joined the federal University of London on 1 September 2016, becoming **City, University of London**.
[src:bencie-woll/city-university-london] In 2024, St George's, University of London, which was established in 1834, merged with the university, with the combined institution adopting its name City St George's, University of London the following year.
[src:bencie-woll/city-university-london] City St George's has strong links with the City of London, and the Lord Mayor of London serves as the university's rector.
[src:bencie-woll/city-university-london] The university has Central London campuses spanning the London Borough of Islington; the City of London; and the London Borough of Wandsworth.
[src:bencie-woll/city-university-london] It is organised into six schools, within which there are around forty academic departments and centres, including the Department of Journalism, Bayes Business School (formerly Cass Business School), and City Law School which incorporates the Inns of Court School of Law.
[src:bencie-woll/city-university-london] The annual income of the institution for 2024–25 was £487.8 million, of which £24.4 million was from research grants and contracts, with an expenditure of £415.3 million.
[src:bencie-woll/city-university-london] The university is a member of the Association of MBAs, EQUIS and Universities UK.
[src:bencie-woll/city-university-london] Alumni of City St George's include members of Parliament of the United Kingdom, politicians and CEOs.
[src:bencie-woll/city-university-london] City St George's traces its origin to the Northampton Institute and the City Law School (established in 1852).
[src:bencie-woll/city-university-london] The first was named after the Marquess of Northampton who donated the land on which the institute was built, between Northampton Square and St John Street in Islington.
[src:bencie-woll/city-university-london] The institute was established to provide for the education and welfare of the local population.
[src:bencie-woll/city-university-london] It was constituted under the City of London Parochial Charities Act (1883), with the objective of "the promotion of the industrial skill, general knowledge, health and well-being of young men and women belonging to the poorer classes".
[src:bencie-woll/city-university-london] Northampton Polytechnic Institute was an institute of technology in Clerkenwell, London, founded in 1894.
[src:bencie-woll/city-university-london] Its first Principal was Robert Mullineux Walmsley.
[src:bencie-woll/city-university-london] Alumni include Colin Cherry, Stuart Davies and Anthony Hunt.
[src:bencie-woll/city-university-london] Arthur George Cocksedge, a British gymnast who competed in the 1920 Summer Olympics, was a member of the Northampton Polytechnic Institute's Gymnastics Club and was Champion of the United Kingdom in 1920.
[src:bencie-woll/city-university-london] In 1937 Maurice Dennis of the (Northampton Polytechnic ABC) was the 1937 ABA Middleweight Champion.
[src:bencie-woll/city-university-london] Frederick Handley Page was a lecturer in aeronautics at the institute.
[src:bencie-woll/city-university-london] The Handley Page Type A, the first powered aircraft designed and built by him, ended up as an instructional airframe at the school.
[src:bencie-woll/city-university-london] The novelist Eric Ambler studied engineering at the institute.
[src:bencie-woll/city-university-london] The six original departments at the institute were Applied Physics and Electrical Engineering; Artistic Crafts; Domestic Economy and Women's Trades; Electro-Chemistry; Horology; and Mechanical Engineering and Metal Trades.
[src:bencie-woll/city-university-london] A separate technical optics department was established in 1903–04.
[src:bencie-woll/city-university-london] In 1909, the first students qualified for University of London BSc degrees in engineering as internal students.
[src:bencie-woll/city-university-london] The Institute had been involved in aeronautics education since that year, and the School of Engineering and Mathematical Sciences celebrated the centenary of aeronautics at City in 2009.
[src:bencie-woll/city-university-london] The institute was used for the 1908 Olympic Games; boxing took place there.
[src:bencie-woll/city-university-london] In 1957, the institute was designated a "College of Advanced Technology".
[src:bencie-woll/city-university-london] The institute's involvement in information science began in 1961, with the introduction of a course on "Collecting and Communicating Scientific Knowledge".
[src:bencie-woll/city-university-london] City received its royal charter in 1966, becoming "The City University" to reflect the institution's close links with the City of London.
[src:bencie-woll/city-university-london] The Apollo 15 astronauts visited City in 1971, and presented the Vice-Chancellor, Tait, with a piece of heat shield from the Apollo 15 rocket.
[src:bencie-woll/city-university-london] In October 1995, it was announced that City University would merge with both the St Bartholomew School of Nursing & Midwifery and the Charterhouse College of Radiography, doubling the number of students in City's Institute of Health Sciences to around 2,500.
[src:bencie-woll/city-university-london] The university formed a strategic alliance with Queen Mary, University of London, in April 2001.
[src:bencie-woll/city-university-london] In May 2001, a fire in the college building gutted the fourth-floor offices and roof.
[src:bencie-woll/city-university-london] In August 2001 City and the Inns of Court School of Law agreed to merge.
[src:bencie-woll/city-university-london] Following a donation from Sir John Cass's Foundation, a multimillion-pound building was built at 106 Bunhill Row for the Business School.
[src:bencie-woll/city-university-london] A new £23 million building to house the School of Social Sciences and the Department of Language and Communication Science was opened in 2004.
[src:bencie-woll/city-university-london] The reconstruction and redevelopment of the university's Grade II listed college building (following the fire in 2001) was completed in July 2006.
[src:bencie-woll/city-university-london] In 2007 the School of Arts received a £10m building refurbishment.
[src:bencie-woll/city-university-london] A new students' union venue opened in October 2008 called "TEN squared", which provides a hub for students to socialise in during the day and hosts a wide range of evening entertainment including club nights, society events and quiz nights.
[src:bencie-woll/city-university-london] In January 2010, premises were shared with the University of East Anglia (UEA) London, following City's partnership with INTO University Partnerships.
[src:bencie-woll/city-university-london] Since then City has resumed its own International Foundation Programme to prepare students for their pre-university year.
[src:bencie-woll/city-university-london] City was ranked among the top 30 higher education institutions in the UK by the *Times Higher Education Table of Tables*.
[src:bencie-woll/city-university-london] In April 2011, it was announced that the current halls of residence and Saddler's Sports Centre will be closed and demolished for rebuilding in June 2011.
[src:bencie-woll/city-university-london] The new student halls and sports facility, now known as CitySport, opened in 2015.
[src:bencie-woll/city-university-london] In September 2016 The City University became a member institution of the federal University of London and changed its name to City, University of London.
[src:bencie-woll/city-university-london] In 2024, St George's, University of London merged with the university with the combined institution rebranding as City St George's, University of London the following year.
[src:bencie-woll/city-university-london] City St George's has sites throughout London, with the main campus located at Northampton Square in the Finsbury area of Islington.
[src:bencie-woll/city-university-london] The Rhind Building which houses the School of Arts and Social Sciences is directly west of Northampton Square.
[src:bencie-woll/city-university-london] A few buildings of the main campus are located in nearby Goswell Road in Clerkenwell.
[src:bencie-woll/city-university-london] The rector of City St George's, University of London, is *ex officio* the Lord Mayor of the City of London.
[src:bencie-woll/city-university-london] The day-to-day running of the university is the responsibility of the president.
[src:bencie-woll/city-university-london] The current president is Sir Anthony Finkelstein.
[src:bencie-woll/city-university-london] The chancellor is Anne, Princess Royal as chancellor of the University of London.
[src:bencie-woll/city-university-london] The role of the chancellor is mainly ceremonial; The president is the principal academic and administrative officer and has been former Chief Scientific Adviser for National Security Sir Anthony Finkelstein since June 2021.
[src:bencie-woll/city-university-london] The Senior Leadership Team assist and advise the president in the "strategic management, development and promotion of the University".
[src:bencie-woll/city-university-london] It includes a provost, four vice-presidents, the seven executive deans of the constituent schools, the chief operating officer, the chief financial officer and other executive management.
[src:bencie-woll/city-university-london] In the financial year ended 31 July 2011, City had a total income (including share of joint ventures) of £178.6 million (2008/09 – £174.4 million) and total expenditure of £183.62 million (2008/09 – £178.82 million).
[src:bencie-woll/city-university-london] During the 2010/11 financial year, City had a capital expenditure of £9.77 million (2008/09 – £16.13 million).
[src:bencie-woll/city-university-london] City St George's, University of London, offers Bachelor's, Master's, and Doctoral degrees as well as certificates and diplomas at both undergraduate and postgraduate level.
[src:bencie-woll/city-university-london] More than two-thirds of City St George's programmes are recognised by the appropriate professional bodies such as the BCS, BPS, CILIP, ICE, RICS, HPC etc. in recognition of the high standards of relevance to the professions.
[src:bencie-woll/city-university-london] The university also has an online careers network where over 2,000 former students offer practical help to current students.
[src:bencie-woll/city-university-london] The City Law School offers courses for undergraduates, postgraduates, master graduates and professional courses leading to qualification as a solicitor or barrister, as well as continuing professional development.
[src:bencie-woll/city-university-london] Its Legal Practice Course has the highest quality rating from the Solicitors Regulation Authority.
[src:bencie-woll/city-university-london] The Department of Radiography (part of the School of Community and Health Sciences) offers two radiography degrees, the BSc (Hons) Radiography (Diagnostic Imaging) and BSc (Hons) Radiography (Radiotherapy and Oncology), both of which are recognised by the Health Professions Council (HPC).
[src:bencie-woll/city-university-london] City St George's, University of London, has links with businesses in the City of London.
[src:bencie-woll/city-university-london] City St George's has also joined forces with other universities such as Queen Mary and the Institute of Education (both part of the University of London) with which it jointly delivers several leading degree programmes.
[src:bencie-woll/city-university-london] London Centre for Arts and Cultural Exchange is a consortium of nine universities.
[src:bencie-woll/city-university-london] It was established in 2004 to foster collaboration and to promote and support the exchange of knowledge between the consortium's partners and London's arts and cultural sectors.
[src:bencie-woll/city-university-london] City St George's was selected as the sole British university to take part in the selective Erasmus Mundus MULTI programme, funded by the European Commission to promote scientific exchange between Europe and the industrialised countries of South-East Asia.
[src:bencie-woll/city-university-london] It is the first Erasmus program to involve universities outside of Europe.
[src:bencie-woll/city-university-london] City St George's has joined the executive group of UCL Partners, one of five accredited academic health science groups in the UK.
[src:bencie-woll/city-university-london] City St George's was invited to join the partnership in recognition of its expertise in nursing, allied health, health services research and evaluation and health management.
[src:bencie-woll/city-university-london] The City St George's Students' Union is run primarily by students through four elected sabbatical officers, the chief executive and an elected assembly (composed of current students), with oversight by a trustee board.
[src:bencie-woll/city-university-london] The Students' Union provides support, representation, facilities, services, entertainment and activities for its members.
[src:bencie-woll/city-university-london] The Students' Union manages most aspects relating to students' societies, such as booking spaces for events on campus, holding funds and distributing grants, and providing training to their committees.
[src:bencie-woll/city-university-london] City St George's currently has two student-run media outlets, including Carrot Radio, which was co-founded by journalism postgraduates Jordan Gass-Pooré and Winston Lo in the autumn of 2018.
[src:bencie-woll/city-university-london] Carrot Radio currently records weekday podcasts.
[src:bencie-woll/city-university-london] The second is the student-led online magazine, *Carrot Magazine*.
[src:bencie-woll/city-university-london] They released their first print magazine in December 2017.
[src:bencie-woll/city-university-london] For a number of years, City St George's students have taken part in the annual Lord Mayor's Show, representing the university in one of the country's largest and liveliest parades.
[src:bencie-woll/city-university-london] City St George's ranked joint 5th out of the 168 universities surveyed in the 2019 People & Planet league table of the most sustainable UK universities having climbed from 7th place in the 2016 league.
[src:bencie-woll/city-university-london] In both the 2016 and 2019 rankings, it was the highest ranking University of London institution, and one of only four London institutions in the top twenty.
[src:bencie-woll/city-university-london] The league table's *Fossil Free Scorecard* report, drawn from Freedom of Information requests, found that £800,000 (6.4%) of City St George's £12.5m endowment was invested in fossil fuels, and that the institution had not made a public commitment to fossil fuel divestment.
[src:bencie-woll/city-university-london] It also noted nearly £1m of research funding into renewables since 2001 with just £64k of total funding from fossil fuel companies; and no honorary degrees or board positions held by fossil fuel executives.
[src:bencie-woll/city-university-london] City St George's announced on 4 July 2023 that it was divesting its investments from fossil fuel producers.
[src:bencie-woll/city-university-london] City St George's Bastwick Street Halls of Residence in Islington was the first home of *MasterChef* following its 2005 revival.
[src:bencie-woll/cognitive-linguistics] Cognitive linguistic theories include George Lakoff and Mark Johnson's conceptual metaphor theory (CMT), Ronald Langacker's cognitive grammar, Charles Fillmore's frame semantics, Leonard Talmy's force dynamics, and Gilles Fauconnier and Mark Turner's conceptual blending.
[src:bencie-woll/cognitive-linguistics] Cognitive linguistic research shares a set of common principles, commitments or hypotheses about language.
[src:bencie-woll/cognitive-linguistics] The exact number and nature of these varies across authors.
[src:bencie-woll/cognitive-linguistics] However, they share much in common and are in broad agreement with each other.
[src:bencie-woll/cognitive-linguistics] This section presents an integrated version of the basic principles covered in popular textbooks and handbooks.
[src:bencie-woll/cognitive-linguistics] Research in cognitive linguistics follows two main commitments: the generalization commitment and the cognitive commitment.
[src:bencie-woll/cognitive-linguistics] Cognitive linguistics looks for linguistic principles that apply across all domains of linguistic structure.
[src:bencie-woll/cognitive-linguistics] Traditionally, linguistics has separated the study of language into different areas.
[src:bencie-woll/cognitive-linguistics] For example, morphology is devoted to word structure, syntax investigates how sentences are constructed and semantics is devoted to the study of linguistic meaning.
[src:bencie-woll/cognitive-linguistics] Cognitive linguistic theories recognize and work with these specific areas of linguistics, but they do not imply that these subdivisions represent the cognitive processes that underpin language.
[src:bencie-woll/cognitive-linguistics] Instead, cognitive linguistics emphasizes that, since the primary function of language is to convey meaning, all linguistic domains are involved in semantics.
[src:bencie-woll/cognitive-linguistics] Cognitive linguistics approach to polysemy is an example of the generalization commitment in action.
[src:bencie-woll/cognitive-linguistics] Traditionally, this phenomenon was considered to be exclusively a matter of lexicography.
[src:bencie-woll/cognitive-linguistics] However, not only words can be polysemous; parts of words like prefixes and suffixes, which are commonly studied in morphology, can have multiple meanings too.
[src:bencie-woll/cognitive-linguistics] In each case, the suffix -er denotes a different semantic role.
[src:bencie-woll/cognitive-linguistics] In 1a it indicates the noun is an AGENT; that is, someone who carries out an action.
[src:bencie-woll/cognitive-linguistics] In 1b it signifies the ORIGIN or place of residence of the noun.
[src:bencie-woll/cognitive-linguistics] In 1c it means that the noun is an INSTRUMENT that serves that specific function.
[src:bencie-woll/cognitive-linguistics] Finally in 1d it is polysemous; it could indicate that the noun is an active AGENT like in 1a, as in "I am my brother's keeper" or it could mean that it is a PATIENT or target of an action as in "She is a keeper".
[src:bencie-woll/cognitive-linguistics] As this example shows, polysemy is not limited to whole words, but instead it generalizes to morphemes.
[src:bencie-woll/cognitive-linguistics] Cognitive linguists argue that this is not an isolated phenomenon and is not exclusive to polysemy, but a general feature of language.
[src:bencie-woll/cognitive-linguistics] Cognitive linguistic approaches are committed to the principle that linguistic structure should reflect general cognitive principles not specific to language.
[src:bencie-woll/cognitive-linguistics] This contrasts with the research program outlined by Noam Chomsky for generative grammar, which proposes a universal grammar, a set of cognitive functions specific to language.
[src:bencie-woll/cognitive-linguistics] The cognitive commitment is exemplified in how attention, a basic cognitive ability, is involved in the process of linguistic profiling.
[src:bencie-woll/cognitive-linguistics] For instance, a scene can be verbally described in many different ways.
[src:bencie-woll/cognitive-linguistics] Each one is able to *profile* different aspects of it by changing the focus of attention by means of its linguistic structure.
[src:bencie-woll/cognitive-linguistics] The pilot crashed the race car.The race car crashed.The race car crashed into pieces.The race car is in pieces.
[src:bencie-woll/cognitive-linguistics] Assuming all of them describe the same scene, ie. share the same referent, it is clear that each one is emphasizing a different aspect of it.
[src:bencie-woll/cognitive-linguistics] In 2a there is an AGENT, the pilot, and a PATIENT, the race car.
[src:bencie-woll/cognitive-linguistics] This is active profiling since the entire action is being brought to attention.
[src:bencie-woll/cognitive-linguistics] In contrast, 2b is passive profiling where the PATIENT is brought to the fore by taking the place of the subject while the AGENT is omitted.
[src:bencie-woll/cognitive-linguistics] In 2c a change of state is being profiled by the syntactic structure subject-verb-complement, where the complement is profiled as a consequence of the verb.
[src:bencie-woll/cognitive-linguistics] Finally, in 2d the state of the PATIENT is being profiled without reference to the action or the AGENT that brought about that change.
[src:bencie-woll/cognitive-linguistics] Because of its commitment to general cognitive principles that apply across all linguistic structures, cognitive linguistics holds the view that linguistic meaning is **non-autonomous**, **perspectival**, **experiential** and **dynamic**.
[src:bencie-woll/cognitive-linguistics] Cognitive linguistics subscribes to the paradigm in cognitive science known as embodied cognition.
[src:bencie-woll/cognitive-linguistics] It views thinking as the product of an organism interacting with its environment.
[src:bencie-woll/cognitive-linguistics] Hence, the body shapes the way an organism thinks.
[src:bencie-woll/cognitive-linguistics] Analyzed through the perspective of conceptual metaphor theory, what all these examples have in common is that they map the notion of verticality onto positive and negative valence.
[src:bencie-woll/cognitive-linguistics] Concretely, the first two instantiate examples of the orientational metaphor UP is GOOD and the last two of its complement, DOWN is BAD.
[src:bencie-woll/cognitive-linguistics] Thinking this way makes sense for an upright walking organism with most of its sense organs located near its apical end.
[src:bencie-woll/cognitive-linguistics] Given this bodily configuration, an active and favorable physical state will be generally connected with the experience of being upright and being at rest or ill will be more readily associated with lying down.
[src:bencie-woll/cognitive-linguistics] In this way, the basic and concrete experience of existing in space as a human being constitutes the basic conceptual scaffolding for thinking of more abstract and complex subjects.
[src:bencie-woll/cognitive-linguistics] The embodiment thesis brings forward deeper epistemological implications.
[src:bencie-woll/cognitive-linguistics] The body is not only the means by which an organism interacts (and therefore thinks) with the world; having a body brings a lived world into existence.
[src:bencie-woll/cognitive-linguistics] Enactivism is the philosophical position in cognitive science that argues that the lived world is enacted or brought forward through the natural history of a species interacting with its environment.
[src:bencie-woll/cognitive-linguistics] Enactivism is opposed to cognitivism, a school of thought in psychology that argues that thinking is the manipulation of symbols, understood as abstract representations of a world external and independent from the organism.
[src:bencie-woll/cognitive-linguistics] It is also somewhat critical of connectionism, a paradigm that describes cognition as an emergent behavior of information networks, because it ignores or downplays the importance of considering the embodiment of such networks.
[src:bencie-woll/cognitive-linguistics] From an enactivist perspective, there is no external reality that language must or even can represent.
[src:bencie-woll/cognitive-linguistics] Linguistic structure is not a mirror of a reality independent of the species that creates it, but a part of the long evolutionary history of the biological, cognitive and social structural couplings of the species with its environment.
[src:bencie-woll/cognitive-linguistics] Cognitive linguistics is divided into two main research areas: cognitive semantics and cognitive approaches to grammar.
[src:bencie-woll/cognitive-linguistics] Cognitive semantics studies how patterns in language map onto conceptual structures and, in turn, how these come from embodied experience.
[src:bencie-woll/cognitive-linguistics] Prominent theories in this field include conceptual metaphor theory, conceptual blending and prototype theory.
[src:bencie-woll/cognitive-linguistics] In turn, cognitive approaches to grammar study the language system itself.
[src:bencie-woll/cognitive-linguistics] The two most well-know cognitive approaches to grammar are cognitive grammar and construction grammars.
[src:bencie-woll/cognitive-linguistics] The groundwork for cognitive linguistics began in the 1970s as linguists developed meaning-centered approaches to language, pushing back against Chomsky's syntax-focused generative grammar.
[src:bencie-woll/cognitive-linguistics] During this time, functional linguistics developed in parallel with comparable aims to cognitive linguistics.
[src:bencie-woll/cognitive-linguistics] Researchers in language acquisition, influenced by Piaget, further contributed a functional/cognitive approach to language learning which influenced cognitive linguistics.
[src:bencie-woll/cognitive-linguistics] Throughout the 1980s individual frameworks matured.
[src:bencie-woll/cognitive-linguistics] Fillmore developed Frame Semantics, and worked with others to produce Construction Grammar.
[src:bencie-woll/cognitive-linguistics] Lakoff continued work on metaphor and metonymy.
[src:bencie-woll/cognitive-linguistics] Langacker's ideas developed into Cognitive Grammar.
[src:bencie-woll/cognitive-linguistics] Talmy published papers on how language provides frameworks for constructing mental representations.
[src:bencie-woll/cognitive-linguistics] Gilles Fauconnier, influenced by Oswald Ducrot, introduced the construct of a mental space.
[src:bencie-woll/cognitive-linguistics] He later worked with Mark Turner to further this into the theory of conceptual blending.
[src:bencie-woll/cognitive-linguistics] The 1980s also saw the emergence of connectionist models of language processing, such as those developed by Jeff Elman and Brian MacWhinney.
[src:bencie-woll/cognitive-linguistics] In 1989, the first International Cognitive Linguistics Conference was held in Duisburg, Germany.
[src:bencie-woll/cognitive-linguistics] During this conference, the founding of the International Cognitive Linguistics Association (ICLA) was decided.
[src:bencie-woll/cognitive-linguistics] In 1990, the journal *Cognitive Linguistics* launched.
[src:bencie-woll/cognitive-linguistics] During the 1990s cognitive linguistics became recognized as a field of specialization within linguistics, and further spread to Korea, Hungary, Thailand, Croatia, and other nations.
